INCAUSTUM, c. 40. The use of ink is ancient; Mosesmentions it in Numbers, v. 23, also Jeremiah, xxxvi. 18 ς the principal colour- ing matter was smoke black combined with tannic aeid. These inks approach the composition of the Chinese or Indian ink as made at present3 the Chinese have had the *credit of the invention of ink, but it is more probably of Egyptian origin.

Coloured inks were used by the Orientals; the emperors of the East had their “ sacrum encaustum,” which was made with purple² and which was kept in vases of gold enriched with gems, the guardian- ship of which was entrusted to the royal officers ³, and the use of which was interdictecl as a capital offenee.
